      "intent_thread_url": "https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/d/msgid/blink-dev/69ba8919.050a0220.1bf526.0067.GAE%40google.com",
      "announcement_url": null,
      "experiment_goals": "During this Origin Trial, we are primarily looking to gain insight into:\n\n## The attribute-based instrumentation model\n- Usage patterns of `containertiming`\n- Frequency and purpose of `containertiming-ignore`\n- Number of annotated elements per page\n\n## PerformanceObserver integration\n- Adoption of PerformanceObserver with container-timing\n- Whether developers batch-observe or use targeted observation\n- Whether buffering behavior meets developer expectations\n\n## Entry shape and timing semantics\n- Whether the exposed timing values align with developer expectations relative to LCP and Element Timing\n- Whether additional metadata fields are needed\n- Whether any fields appear unused or redundant\n\n## Edge cases and ergonomics\n- Nested containers\n- Dynamically inserted elements\n- Interaction with visibility changes and layout shifts",
      "experiment_risks": "No storage / state risk: Container Timing does not introduce any new storage surface, persistent state, or origin-scoped quota/permissions. Ending the trial cannot cause sites to “lose access” to any data they previously stored or relied on for functionality.\n\nBehavioral impact is limited to observability: Sites that rely on Container Timing for analytics/monitoring will stop receiving PerformanceContainerTiming entries once the feature is no longer available. This may reduce visibility into container-level performance but does not affect page rendering, resource loading, or correctness.\n\nDegradation mode is predictable and detectable: Sites can feature-detect support (e.g., checking supported entry types / observing errors when registering the observer) and fall back to existing signals like LCP / Element Timing / custom userland timing. We will document recommended feature detection and fallback patterns for trial participants.\n\nNo security/privacy regressions beyond standard Perf Timeline considerations: The API is an extension of the Performance Timeline and is intended to follow existing constraints (origin isolation, clamping, and exposure rules consistent with other performance entries). Trial end does not create additional risk; it only removes the entries.",
      "origin_trial_id": "3312960475884421121",
      "origin_trial_feedback_url": null,
